{"id":"cond-mat/0005192","submitter":"Roland Faller","authors":"Roland Faller and Florian Mueller-Plathe","title":"Chain stiffness intensifies the reptation characteristics of polymer\n  dynamics in the melt","comments":"10 pages revtex, 5 figures, partly color","journal-ref":"ChemPhysChem 2(3) 180-184 (2001)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":null,"abstract":"  The reptation concept in polymer dynamics is studied for model chains with\nadded stiffness. The main idea of a chain diffusing inside a tube can be\ntransferred from fully flexible chains. However, the picture, which\nrenormalizes the chain of locally stiff Kuhn segments onto a flexible chain of\nfewer segments fails. The entanglement length shrinks with increasing\npersistence length. If entanglement length and persistence length come to the\nsame order of magnitude the picture of a tight tube is better suited, in which\nchain segments can move only along the contour, any transverse motion being\nmuch reduced. Thus, as stiffness increases, the monomers loose their freedom to\nperform random walks inside the tube, the ``Rouse-like'' part of their\ndynamics. As a result, for persistence lengths of more than five monomers no\nlength scale can be described by the Rouse model.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 May 2000 12:19:34 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 12 Feb 2001 17:55:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
